{"questionId":"14661688","questionHtml":"<p>Using the second derivative at each point found in part (a), show that the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;has two local maximum points and one local minimum point.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to differentiate&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;using product rule&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>\"</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>\"</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;so maximum <strong>AND</strong></p>\n<p>at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>\"</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;so maximum&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>\"</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;so minimum&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: The values for the second derivative must be correct in order to award the <em><strong>R</strong></em> marks.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14661688","referenceCode":"23N.1.AHL.TZ2.11b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Using the second derivative at each point found in part (a), show that the curve y=fx has two local maximum points and one local minimum point.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}